Gia

“You are too pretty to be fat.”

“Make sure you buy shirts that cover your butt!”

“Are you sure this dress isn’t too tight?”

“Your belly has gotten so big, I can sit on it.”

They are just words I tell myself. But when you hear them so many times in your life you begin to believe them. So, I have, and it has defiantly ruined me emotionally. I walk around wondering what people think when I catch someone staring at me. Most of the time, my eyes are looking at the sidewalk as I walk to the nearest train station or Target or Whole Foods.

Are my clothes to tight? My jeans aren’t falling off, right? Did I put on my belt? Does my stomach show a lot in this V-neck shirt I think I like cute in? Let me just tug on my shirt real quick, maybe my stomach won’t show as much. Maybe I should get this in a larger size, so I won’t look so big.

Those thoughts race through my head every day. I never had the luxury of feeling simply okay in my skin. Something is always wrong about me. And maybe one day I won’t feel like this, but this is the process I go through everyday. It’s my life.

I am constantly thinking of the food I am about to eat, because people never gave me the luxury of just eating without telling me "maybe you shouldn't eat that. I am constantly thinking of the clothes I put every day, cause people never gave me the luxury of just wearing what I want without being judged. Or telling me that I should wear these wide legged pants, and this large t-shirt because my butt is unflattering in skinny jeans and the shirt I was wearing before wasn't covering it.

) } export default BlogTwo;
